Four counties partially shut their head offices this week as 571 more people tested positive for Covid-19 yesterday. Nandi, Uasin Gishu, Trans Nzoia and Nakuru partially closed their offices and ordered mass testing of their staff. Health CS Mutahi Kagwe said the new cases announced yesterday pushed the total to 45,647 Covid-19 cases. The positives were from a sample of 3,963 tests that were conducted in 24 hours. Three more patients succumbed to the disease raising the total number of fatalities to 842. According to a statement from the Ministry of Health, cumulative tests now stand at 627,781 since the first case was reported in March. Nairobi and Uasin Gishu counties lead with 116 cases each followed by Mombasa with 74 cases, Kiambu 50 cases, Laikipia 43 cases, Kericho 41, Kisumu 23, Nakuru 21, Busia 16, Trans Nzoia 10 and Kajiado 9 cases. While Nandi county has 8 cases, Murang'a, Kilifi, Kirinyaga each have five cases, West Pokot 4 cases, Kakamega 4, Isiolo 3, Siaya 3, Elgeyo Marakwet, kISII, eMBU, Vihiga and Bungoma each two cases and Kwale, Nyeri, DSamburu, Machakos and Turkana counties each one case. The statement signed by Health CS Mutahi Kagwe further indicates that 84  patients are currently under the Intensive Care Unit out of whom 43 are on ventilators while 41 are on supplementary oxygen. Kagwe said there is a total of 1,059 people currently admitted to various health facilities across the country. Some other 2,562 patients are under home-based isolation and care. "Today 438 people have recovered from the disease out of who, 373 are from the Home-Based care program while 65 from various hospitals," Kagwe said. As a result, the total recoveries now stand at 32,522. In Eldoret, CEO Dr Wilson Aruasa confirmed that a male medic who worked in the Occupational Therapy department of Moi Teaching and Referral hospital succumbed at the hospital where he was undergoing treatment. “Sadly we have lost one staff who was critical and had a comorbidity”, said Dr Aruasa. Uasin Gishu County health executive Evelyne Rotich said so far 20 people have died on Covid-19 in the county. Dr Aruasa added that the hospital has 36 patients admitted at the moment while 65 others were under MTRH Home Based Isolation & Care (HBC). In the county, the entire county assembly was closed on monday closed after an MCA succumbed to the disease. Nandi County announced a partial shut down of its headquarters in Kapsabet town on Sunday after eight senior officers tested positive for Covid-19 in tests carried out last week.